2026-04-16 12:21:56 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['power-supply-to-control-module cable pair'] hypothesis_explanation='The observation shows that the two cables between the power‑supply output and the control‑module input are polarity‑swapped: PSU + is connected to Control − and PSU − to Control +. This exactly explains the symptoms: (1) the green LED in the PSU lights because it is wired directly across the supply regardless of downstream polarity; (2) the red inverted‑cables indicator LED in the control module is designed to turn on when its 12 V and 0 V lines are reversed, which is the case here; (3) with the control module’s internal 12 V/0 V rails reversed, the load module sees reversed polarity as well, so the series diode at the load input is reverse‑biased and blocks current, preventing the lamp from turning on even when the switch is closed. Correcting this polarity at the power‑supply–to–control‑module cable pair (swapping the two connections) should restore normal operation, turning off the red LED and allowing the lamp to light when the switch is operated.'
