2026-04-16 12:22:14 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['Control module internal wiring between input pair and output pair (polarity routing)', 'Load module series diode on 12V line'] hypothesis_explanation='The external cables and their polarities have been corrected and verified, the PSU LED is on (so supply is present), and the red “inverted cables” LED on the control module is still lit while the lamp does not turn on. Given the design, that red LED should only conduct when the control input pair is reversed relative to the PSU output or when + and − are shorted/bridged incorrectly inside the control module. Since the external pair has already been fixed, a remaining mis‑wiring or internal short in the control module between its input terminals (e.g., + tied to − through or around the indicator branch) is strongly indicated. This could both keep the red LED on and prevent proper +12V from being passed through the switch to the output pair. In addition, if the load module’s series diode on the 12V line has failed open, that would independently prevent current to the lamps even with correct upstream wiring. I therefore hypothesize faults in the control module’s internal polarity routing (e.g., miswired traces/leads that tie + to − or bypass the switch) and/or an open series diode in the load module. Replacing/repairing these elements should extinguish the red LED with correct cabling and restore lamp operation when the switch is closed.'
